  <!--
  ============================================================================
  ANSWER KEY  (remove this block when handing the file to trainees)
  ============================================================================
   #1  Hardcoded secrets in client JS — Stripe/AWS/OpenAI/Maps keys + DB
       connection string with embedded password, all readable by anyone.
       Fix: keep secrets server-side; never ship them to the browser.

   #2  Outdated dependency (jQuery 1.7.2) loaded over a CDN with no
       Subresource Integrity (SRI) hash. Old version has known XSS CVEs;
       missing SRI allows CDN tampering. Fix: update + add integrity="sha384-...".

   #3  Information disclosure in HTML comment — internal admin URL, a
       debug flag, and default admin/admin123 creds. Fix: strip comments
       in prod builds; never store creds anywhere in source.

   #4  Credentials sent via GET over plain HTTP — they leak into the URL,
       server logs, proxies, and browser history. Fix: POST over HTTPS only.

   #5  Sensitive hidden form fields — a "role" field a user can tamper with
       (privilege escalation) and a static, never-rotating CSRF token (useless
       as a CSRF defense). Fix: enforce roles server-side; per-session CSRF tokens.

   #6  Client-side-only authentication with a hardcoded password. Anyone can
       read it in View Source or just call the success path. Fix: authenticate
       on the server; never compare passwords in client code.

   #7  Auth token stored in localStorage in plaintext — readable by any XSS
       payload. Fix: use httpOnly, Secure, SameSite cookies for session tokens.

   #8  User-enumeration via distinct error messages ("no such user" vs
       "wrong password"). Fix: return one generic "invalid credentials" message.

   #9  Reflected XSS — ?name= is concatenated into innerHTML unsanitized.
       Try ?name=<img src=x onerror=alert(1)>. Fix: use textContent, or
       encode/sanitize all untrusted input; add a Content-Security-Policy.

   #10 Backdoor debug bypass — ?debug=1 dumps secrets to console and grants
       an admin session with no auth. Fix: remove debug backdoors; never
       gate privileged behavior on a client-visible query param.

   BONUS: marketing copy makes absolute security claims ("100% breach-proof",
   "no one can ever break it") — a social-engineering / false-assurance red flag.
  ============================================================================
  -->

